18
00:00:58,755 --> 00:01:01,125
Let's start with the basic
problem we are trying to solve.

19
00:01:01,625 --> 00:01:04,775
Modern backend systems are
no longer simple monoliths.

20
00:01:04,825 --> 00:01:09,115
A single user request can easily
touch five to 10 microservices each

21
00:01:09,175 --> 00:01:13,645
with its own database cache, queue
configuration, and deployment pipeline.

22
00:01:14,455 --> 00:01:18,965
When an incident happens for example,
when latency increases or error rate

23
00:01:18,965 --> 00:01:22,775
spike, the challenge is not just
what is wrong with this one service.

24
00:01:23,315 --> 00:01:26,080
The real challenge is which
combination of services is involved.

25
00:01:26,580 --> 00:01:30,440
Where in the call chain is the bottleneck
or failure, and which telemetry signal

26
00:01:30,440 --> 00:01:31,910
should we really pay attention to?

27
00:01:32,340 --> 00:01:35,550
Logs, metrics traces or ad hoc queries.

28
00:01:36,050 --> 00:01:39,480
On paper, we have a lot of
tools observability platform,

29
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:43,170
centralized logging, metrics and
dashboards, distributed tracing

30
00:01:43,170 --> 00:01:44,430
and sophisticated alerting.

31
00:01:44,940 --> 00:01:48,810
But in practice, during an incident,
the on-call engineer has to maintain

32
00:01:48,810 --> 00:01:53,400
a mentally connect signals from
all these places across multiple

33
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:55,050
services and under time pressure.

34
00:01:55,710 --> 00:01:58,125
That is the core SRE
challenge I want to address.

35
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:03,810
Making it easier and faster to understand
what's going on in a complex microservices

36
00:02:03,810 --> 00:02:05,670
environment when something breaks,

37
00:02:06,170 --> 00:02:09,619
let's look more closely at what
actually happens during an incident

38
00:02:09,619 --> 00:02:15,079
today and where the pain really is
First, engineers often spend two

39
00:02:15,079 --> 00:02:19,459
to four hours just on investigative
investigation for non-trivial incidents.

40
00:02:20,149 --> 00:02:23,839
This is time spent not fixing the
problem, but trying to understand

41
00:02:23,839 --> 00:02:25,609
where the problem really is.

42
00:02:26,599 --> 00:02:30,259
Second, there is a lot of manual
correlation across different data stores.

43
00:02:30,349 --> 00:02:35,089
For example, you run SQL queries against
a data warehouse or time series store.

44
00:02:35,719 --> 00:02:38,779
You open a logging tool
like Ban or Splunk.

45
00:02:39,279 --> 00:02:42,534
You open dashboards for
metrics in Grafana or Datadog.

46
00:02:43,390 --> 00:02:47,100
You might also open a tracing
UI and maybe some deployment

47
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:48,809
logs or feature flag dashboards.

48
00:02:49,559 --> 00:02:51,689
None of these tools share
a common mental model.

49
00:02:51,929 --> 00:02:56,760
The only thing that ties them together is
the human on-call engineer who manually

50
00:02:56,760 --> 00:02:58,890
jumps between them and connects the dots.

51
00:02:59,579 --> 00:03:02,225
Third, expertise takes
a long time to build.

52
00:03:03,180 --> 00:03:05,549
Senior engineers know
which dashboards to trust.

53
00:03:05,850 --> 00:03:09,209
They know which metrics
truly indicate user impact.

54
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:12,989
They remember which services are
actually behind certain APIs.

55
00:03:13,650 --> 00:03:18,000
Junior engineers typically don't have this
context yet, so they end up waiting for a

56
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:19,739
backend expert to join the call and help.

57
00:03:20,239 --> 00:03:24,920
Fourth, we have overwhelming amounts
of telemetry, too many logs, too many

58
00:03:24,920 --> 00:03:26,899
metrics, and often too many dashboards.

59
00:03:27,469 --> 00:03:29,089
The problem is not lack of data.

60
00:03:29,450 --> 00:03:32,989
The problem is making sense of
it quickly and connect correctly.

61
00:03:33,489 --> 00:03:36,609
All of this together means
that we have limited effective

62
00:03:36,609 --> 00:03:40,970
visibility during incidents, and
this slows down our response.

63
00:03:41,600 --> 00:03:45,620
This is exactly the gap where AI
can help, not by magically fixing

64
00:03:45,620 --> 00:03:49,160
the systems, but by supporting the
reasoning and correlation work that

65
00:03:49,160 --> 00:03:50,810
engineers are currently doing manually.

66
00:03:51,310 --> 00:03:53,440
Leveraging LLMs and MCP technology.

67
00:03:53,769 --> 00:03:57,760
Now let's talk about the proposed
solution, AI assisted incident response.

68
00:03:58,259 --> 00:04:02,309
The core idea is to combine two
things, large language models or LLMs,

69
00:04:02,399 --> 00:04:05,369
which are good to add, understanding
natural language and working with

70
00:04:05,369 --> 00:04:09,509
structured data and the model context
protocol or MCP, which gives these

71
00:04:09,509 --> 00:04:11,279
models a set standardized, safe way.

72
00:04:12,029 --> 00:04:15,880
To access telemetry data
and schemas in practice.

73
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:18,970
What does AI agent actually
do during an incident?

74
00:04:19,470 --> 00:04:23,100
First, it takes a natural language
description of the problem from engineer.

75
00:04:23,670 --> 00:04:28,200
F for example, we are seeing
increased IXX errors from the backend

76
00:04:28,340 --> 00:04:31,789
checkout service in the Euro region
for after the last deployment.

77
00:04:32,270 --> 00:04:36,150
This could be a simple problem that
analyst can provide to the AI agent.

78
00:04:36,690 --> 00:04:40,950
Then using MCP, the AI agent can in
inspect elementary schemas, it can

79
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:44,340
see which metrics logs and tables
exist and how they are structured.

80
00:04:45,135 --> 00:04:48,315
Based on that, the agent can
generate s QL queries or equivalent

81
00:04:48,315 --> 00:04:50,085
queries to the telemetry systems.

82
00:04:50,625 --> 00:04:52,785
These queries are tailored
to investigate the specific

83
00:04:52,785 --> 00:04:55,335
incident, described the agent.

84
00:04:55,545 --> 00:04:57,495
They can then refine these queries.

85
00:04:57,795 --> 00:05:01,725
Alternatively, it can zoom in on a
specific service region or version.

86
00:05:02,175 --> 00:05:04,215
It can compare before
and after a deployment.

87
00:05:04,665 --> 00:05:08,655
It can correlate metrics, logs,
traces across the services.

88
00:05:09,585 --> 00:05:12,435
This is not about fully
automating instant resolution.

89
00:05:12,525 --> 00:05:17,175
It is about assisting the human on-call
engineer by reducing the manual effort of

90
00:05:17,175 --> 00:05:22,095
writing and rewriting queries, surfacing
relevant events or data more quickly,

91
00:05:22,605 --> 00:05:26,595
and highlighting correlations that
might not be obvious at first glance.

92
00:05:27,095 --> 00:05:30,425
To make this approach safe and
reliable, we need a controlled way

93
00:05:30,425 --> 00:05:33,085
for AI agents to talk to our systems.

94
00:05:33,475 --> 00:05:35,965
That's where the model context
protocol or MCP comes in.

95
00:05:36,355 --> 00:05:40,645
MCP is a standardized interface that
sits between AI models and tools or

96
00:05:40,645 --> 00:05:45,385
data sources such as telemetry systems
in the context of incident response.

97
00:05:45,415 --> 00:05:47,215
MCP does a few important things.

98
00:05:47,845 --> 00:05:49,555
First schema introspection.

99
00:05:50,455 --> 00:05:54,445
The AI agent can ask questions like what
tables are available, what columns do they

100
00:05:54,445 --> 00:05:56,875
have, what metrics exist for the service?

101
00:05:57,535 --> 00:05:58,675
This removes guesswork.

102
00:05:59,245 --> 00:06:02,845
The agent sees the real schema, not
some assumed or hardcoded structure.

103
00:06:03,415 --> 00:06:05,425
Second, controlled query execution.

104
00:06:05,925 --> 00:06:11,025
Instead of giving the model direct
unrestricted database access MCP exposes

105
00:06:11,025 --> 00:06:16,245
safe read only operations, the AI can
request certain SQL queries to be run.

106
00:06:16,335 --> 00:06:19,980
The system enforces limits, such as
Readly access and safe query patents.

107
00:06:20,890 --> 00:06:24,400
Sensitive or personally identifiable
data can be filtered or must.

108
00:06:24,910 --> 00:06:27,100
This gives us the
guardrails and auditability.

109
00:06:27,730 --> 00:06:30,070
Third, a standardized
pattern across tools.

110
00:06:30,580 --> 00:06:34,390
Whether your data lives in BigQuery,
snowflake, Lakehouse, Prometheus,

111
00:06:34,390 --> 00:06:37,810
or a lock store, the AI speaks to
them through a consistent protocol.

112
00:06:38,500 --> 00:06:41,770
This means we don't have to
custom integrate the AI with each

113
00:06:41,770 --> 00:06:43,270
system in a totally different way.

114
00:06:43,750 --> 00:06:45,910
We can log and monitor
what the AI is doing.

115
00:06:46,455 --> 00:06:49,605
And we can swap or extend tools
behind the scenes without changing

116
00:06:49,605 --> 00:06:50,895
how the AI agent is written.

117
00:06:51,555 --> 00:06:55,395
In short, MCP is what turns the
LLM from a single chat bot into

118
00:06:55,395 --> 00:06:58,725
a tool using telemetry aware
agent with safety boundaries.

119
00:06:59,225 --> 00:07:02,975
Now let's walk through the typical AI
assisted incident workflow, step by step.

120
00:07:03,475 --> 00:07:05,215
Step one is a natural language input.

121
00:07:05,810 --> 00:07:08,510
The engineer starts by describing
the incident in plain language.

122
00:07:08,510 --> 00:07:12,410
For example, we are seeing a
spike in SGDP 500 errors for the

123
00:07:12,410 --> 00:07:17,610
checkout service in the US West two
region, starting at say 10 15 UTC.

124
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:20,880
The last deployment happened
about 30 minutes before that.

125
00:07:21,240 --> 00:07:23,190
Can you investigate what's going on?

126
00:07:23,690 --> 00:07:28,760
The AI agent reads this and extracts
key details like the affected service.

127
00:07:29,390 --> 00:07:33,260
The region, the timeframe, the
relevant event like deployment

128
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:34,400
shortly before the spike.

129
00:07:34,900 --> 00:07:37,300
Step two is SQL and
telemetric query generation.

130
00:07:37,870 --> 00:07:40,810
Using the telemetry
schema exposed via IMCP.

131
00:07:40,930 --> 00:07:45,250
The agent then generates one or more
queries, for example, a query to get

132
00:07:45,250 --> 00:07:47,020
error rates by endpoint over time.

133
00:07:47,020 --> 00:07:50,080
A query to compare latency
before and after 10 15.

134
00:07:50,830 --> 00:07:54,940
A query to see request volume broken
down by version or deployment id

135
00:07:55,390 --> 00:07:58,810
a query to look for changes in
downstream dependency performance.

136
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:02,320
The engineer doesn't have to
remember table names, column

137
00:08:02,320 --> 00:08:03,640
names, or joint conditions.

138
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:07,480
They can simply ask questions in
natural language, and the AI maps

139
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:09,300
those questions to concrete queries.

140
00:08:09,800 --> 00:08:11,405
Step three is the iterative analysis.

141
00:08:12,245 --> 00:08:15,395
Once the results come back,
the ad just doesn't stop there.

142
00:08:15,515 --> 00:08:16,955
It enters an at loop,

143
00:08:17,455 --> 00:08:18,625
it analyzes the results.

144
00:08:18,625 --> 00:08:25,935
For example, the 500 errors increased
sharply at 10 0 12 UTC mostly on the slash

145
00:08:25,935 --> 00:08:28,110
pain point and only for version one point.

146
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:32,865
2.4, it then proposes or
runs the next logical query.

147
00:08:32,865 --> 00:08:36,995
For example now check if there were
configuration changes or dependency

148
00:08:36,995 --> 00:08:38,315
failures at that same time.

149
00:08:39,095 --> 00:08:43,055
It keeps going correlating metrics
and logs across services until it

150
00:08:43,055 --> 00:08:45,315
can propose a. Plausible hypothesis.

151
00:08:45,815 --> 00:08:50,115
After a few attritions, the AI might say
something like the 500 error spike is

152
00:08:50,115 --> 00:08:55,275
limited to US West two on version 1.2
0.4, mainly on the payment endpoint.

153
00:08:55,965 --> 00:08:59,205
At the same time, the payment
provides timeout errors increased,

154
00:08:59,445 --> 00:09:01,005
starting just after the rollout.

155
00:09:01,635 --> 00:09:04,335
This suggests a change in
the payment integration is

156
00:09:04,335 --> 00:09:06,255
causing downstream timeouts.

157
00:09:06,755 --> 00:09:09,605
Now throughout this process, the
human engineer can interrupt,

158
00:09:09,635 --> 00:09:11,675
steer, or refine the investigation.

159
00:09:12,065 --> 00:09:15,545
The AI handles the heavy
lifting of writing, running, and

160
00:09:15,545 --> 00:09:17,135
correlating many queries quickly.

161
00:09:17,855 --> 00:09:20,135
The value is speed and coverage.

162
00:09:20,225 --> 00:09:24,005
The AI can explore more angles
more quickly than a human manually

163
00:09:24,155 --> 00:09:25,745
pivoting across the interfaces.

164
00:09:26,245 --> 00:09:29,185
For this whole approach to
work well, context engineering

165
00:09:29,185 --> 00:09:30,535
is absolutely critical.

166
00:09:30,955 --> 00:09:34,795
If you simply connect an LLM to a
production database with no documentation

167
00:09:34,795 --> 00:09:39,145
and no structure, we should expect poor
results and possibly unsafe behavior.

168
00:09:40,075 --> 00:09:43,105
There are three main components
of context engineering here.

169
00:09:43,525 --> 00:09:44,905
First is the schema documentation.

170
00:09:44,905 --> 00:09:48,625
The AI needs to understand
not just names, but meanings.

171
00:09:48,655 --> 00:09:51,955
For example, what does a particular
column actually represent?

172
00:09:52,930 --> 00:09:55,840
Is the timestamp in seconds,
milliseconds, or something else?

173
00:09:56,380 --> 00:09:58,960
How do we join logs and
metrics for the same request?

174
00:09:59,650 --> 00:10:02,530
Which field represents a service
name, region, or version?

175
00:10:03,030 --> 00:10:06,420
Good documentation helps the AI
generate correct and meaningful

176
00:10:06,420 --> 00:10:09,000
queries and avoid misinterpreting data.

177
00:10:09,500 --> 00:10:11,210
Second is the curated query libraries.

178
00:10:11,710 --> 00:10:14,710
We don't want the AI to reinvent
every query from scratch.

179
00:10:14,770 --> 00:10:18,790
Instead, we provide a library of
pretested reliable queries for

180
00:10:18,790 --> 00:10:20,260
common investigation patterns.

181
00:10:20,290 --> 00:10:24,100
For example, show error rate by
endpoint over the last 12 hours.

182
00:10:24,180 --> 00:10:27,330
Compare P 95 latency before
and after the deployment.

183
00:10:27,900 --> 00:10:31,950
Show the top end services by error
volume during the incident window.

184
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:35,220
Compare traffic patterns this
week versus the last week.

185
00:10:35,720 --> 00:10:39,890
The AI can then reuse these queries,
adapt them to different services or

186
00:10:39,890 --> 00:10:42,440
regions, and combine them in new ways.

187
00:10:43,130 --> 00:10:45,860
This improves the reliability
and reduces the chances of

188
00:10:45,920 --> 00:10:47,660
inefficient and incorrect queries.

189
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:49,525
Third is the architecture diagrams.

190
00:10:49,605 --> 00:10:54,250
Architecture diagrams give a clear picture
of which services, talk to which, what

191
00:10:54,250 --> 00:11:00,190
are the deployment or dependencies are,
and where the data flows, data flow goes.

192
00:11:00,690 --> 00:11:04,590
When the AI knows, for example,
that checkout needs or depends on

193
00:11:04,590 --> 00:11:09,880
payments, inventory, and user profile
services, it can, sorry about that.

194
00:11:10,380 --> 00:11:14,630
It can automatically suggest
investigations like check latency and

195
00:11:14,630 --> 00:11:17,840
error rates for the payment service
in the same region and timeframe.

196
00:11:18,200 --> 00:11:21,590
Check if inventory latency correlates
with checkout slow slowdowns.

197
00:11:22,445 --> 00:11:26,465
These diagrams shorten the lifetime
from symptom to likely cause,

198
00:11:26,525 --> 00:11:28,985
because the dependencies are
explicit and machine readable.

199
00:11:29,855 --> 00:11:34,085
The key point is AI assistance is only
as good as the context you provide.

200
00:11:34,865 --> 00:11:38,315
Investing in documentation, curated
queries and architecture diagrams

201
00:11:38,345 --> 00:11:41,975
is what turns AI from a generic
assistant into a powerful domain

202
00:11:41,975 --> 00:11:43,535
specific incident Investigator.

203
00:11:44,035 --> 00:11:46,945
Everything we have discussed so
far depends on the telemetry, and

204
00:11:46,945 --> 00:11:49,615
telemetry itself is challenging
in distributed systems.

205
00:11:50,245 --> 00:11:52,225
There are several types
of complexity here.

206
00:11:52,275 --> 00:11:54,915
First di diversity and heterogeneity.

207
00:11:55,665 --> 00:11:59,205
In a large organization, different
teams log in different formats.

208
00:11:59,535 --> 00:12:01,935
Metric names are
inconsistent across services.

209
00:12:02,565 --> 00:12:04,665
Some teams use one tracing library.

210
00:12:04,665 --> 00:12:05,290
Others use another.

211
00:12:05,955 --> 00:12:09,675
Some services are well instrumented,
others barely make useful data.

212
00:12:10,215 --> 00:12:14,475
This makes cross service correlation
difficult for both humans and ai.

213
00:12:15,345 --> 00:12:20,485
Second is the timing issues and data
quality metrics might be aggregated

214
00:12:20,485 --> 00:12:22,255
in one minute or five minute buckets.

215
00:12:22,345 --> 00:12:26,545
Logs might be near real time or delayed
traces might be heavily sampled.

216
00:12:27,295 --> 00:12:31,195
Aligning all of these signals on a single
accurate timeline can be very hard.

217
00:12:31,695 --> 00:12:36,195
Third, the need for aggregation and
normalization To compare behavior

218
00:12:36,225 --> 00:12:41,115
across services and regions, we need
consistent labels such as service

219
00:12:41,235 --> 00:12:46,695
region, version deployment, underscore
id, and user underscore id, et cetera.

220
00:12:47,195 --> 00:12:50,555
Shared naming conventions for
key metrics such as latency,

221
00:12:50,555 --> 00:12:52,085
error rates, and request counts.

222
00:12:52,955 --> 00:12:58,265
Without this, it becomes very difficult to
ask comparative questions, spot patterns,

223
00:12:58,295 --> 00:13:00,095
or automate any kind of reasoning.

224
00:13:00,845 --> 00:13:02,375
Fourth is alerting challenges.

225
00:13:02,675 --> 00:13:07,715
If alerts are too sensitive and the
team experiences alert fatigue, if

226
00:13:07,715 --> 00:13:11,255
they are too relaxed, serious problems
might not be detected in time.

227
00:13:11,755 --> 00:13:16,255
AI can help analyze patterns and
suggest better thresholds, but it still

228
00:13:16,255 --> 00:13:18,025
depends on the underlying data quality.

229
00:13:18,525 --> 00:13:20,380
Finally the culture and collaboration.

230
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:21,120
Good.

231
00:13:21,120 --> 00:13:24,570
Telemetry is not just a tooling
problem, it's also a cultural one.

232
00:13:25,080 --> 00:13:28,710
It requires agreement on standard
across teams, collaboration

233
00:13:28,710 --> 00:13:30,480
between development and operations.

234
00:13:30,930 --> 00:13:34,020
Continuous improvement based on
what each incident teaches us.

235
00:13:34,650 --> 00:13:38,580
AI assisted incident response does
not make telemetry problems disappear.

236
00:13:39,180 --> 00:13:44,160
What it does is help us navigate complex
telemetry more efficiently, but only

237
00:13:44,160 --> 00:13:47,760
if we invest in making that telemetry
reasonably consistent and discoverable.

238
00:13:48,705 --> 00:13:48,995
Okay.

239
00:13:49,495 --> 00:13:50,815
Now let's talk about the impact.

240
00:13:51,315 --> 00:13:54,945
What can we realistically expect
from AI assisted incident response?

241
00:13:54,975 --> 00:13:59,715
When it is done well from early
prototypes and case studies, we

242
00:13:59,715 --> 00:14:03,585
typically see things like a significant
reduction in investigative effort.

243
00:14:04,365 --> 00:14:08,055
In other words, the time between
alert fired and we have a reasonably

244
00:14:08,055 --> 00:14:12,855
confident hypothesis decreases a
reduction in meantime to resolution.

245
00:14:13,275 --> 00:14:17,385
Especially for incident types that occur
repeatedly where the AI can recognize

246
00:14:17,385 --> 00:14:19,155
patterns and reuse previous knowledge.

247
00:14:20,145 --> 00:14:23,955
The exact numbers, like X percent
reduction in effort or Y percent reduction

248
00:14:23,955 --> 00:14:28,935
in the resolution time will depend on how
mature your telemetry stack is, how much

249
00:14:28,935 --> 00:14:32,955
context engineering you have done, and
how comfortable your engineers are with

250
00:14:32,955 --> 00:14:34,995
using the AI assistant in their workflow.

251
00:14:35,865 --> 00:14:38,565
However, the quality feedback
tends to be consistent.

252
00:14:38,895 --> 00:14:41,595
Engineers say they go, got a
plausible root cause faster.

253
00:14:42,345 --> 00:14:46,275
Junior engineers say they could drive
investigations without constantly waiting

254
00:14:46,275 --> 00:14:51,825
For a senior expert teams notice that far
more queries and correlations get run in

255
00:14:51,825 --> 00:14:53,805
the first 10 or 15 minutes than before.

256
00:14:54,305 --> 00:14:57,935
In short, this approach compresses
the investigation phase and frees

257
00:14:57,935 --> 00:15:02,150
your experts to focus more on decision
making, remediation, and long-term fixes.

258
00:15:02,650 --> 00:15:06,160
Let's make the difference more concrete
by comparing the situation before the AI

259
00:15:06,160 --> 00:15:08,500
assistance and late after AI assistance.

260
00:15:09,220 --> 00:15:13,790
Before AI assistance investigations
can typically easily take up to two

261
00:15:13,790 --> 00:15:15,590
to four hours for complex incidents.

262
00:15:16,370 --> 00:15:19,700
Engineers manually write SQL and
build complex filters and dashboards.

263
00:15:20,360 --> 00:15:23,300
A small number of senior
experts become bottlenecks.

264
00:15:23,810 --> 00:15:25,940
People wait for them
to interpret telemetry.

265
00:15:26,420 --> 00:15:29,510
Correlating data across service
requires a lot of copying, pasting,

266
00:15:29,510 --> 00:15:31,220
and switching context between tools.

267
00:15:32,120 --> 00:15:35,810
The result is longer resolution
time, more user impact, and higher

268
00:15:35,810 --> 00:15:40,390
stress for the on-call team after AI
assistance the S QL query generation

269
00:15:40,390 --> 00:15:42,460
is automated from natural language.

270
00:15:42,960 --> 00:15:46,170
The AI supports fast
conversational refinements

271
00:15:46,270 --> 00:15:48,850
correlation across service
and data sources improve.

272
00:15:49,270 --> 00:15:52,150
Because the AI is able to navigate
telemetry schemas quickly and

273
00:15:52,150 --> 00:15:55,690
systematically, time to resolution
decreases, especially for

274
00:15:55,690 --> 00:15:57,670
recurring or pattern based issues.

275
00:15:58,150 --> 00:16:00,400
And importantly, junior
engineers are empowered.

276
00:16:00,850 --> 00:16:04,330
They can lead much of the investigation
by asking the AI questions.

277
00:16:05,050 --> 00:16:08,380
They only need to pull in experts
in for judgment calls and complex

278
00:16:08,380 --> 00:16:10,450
decisions, not for every basic query.

279
00:16:10,950 --> 00:16:13,680
This transformation is not about
removing people from the loop.

280
00:16:13,890 --> 00:16:16,110
It is about making the loop much faster.

281
00:16:16,485 --> 00:16:18,975
And less reliant on a
handful of individuals.

282
00:16:19,475 --> 00:16:23,525
Now I will briefly summarize the overall
architecture pattern behind this approach.

283
00:16:23,615 --> 00:16:25,084
There are three main pillars.

284
00:16:25,135 --> 00:16:26,635
First is LLM integration.

285
00:16:27,395 --> 00:16:31,205
At the center is the large
language model connected via MCP

286
00:16:31,205 --> 00:16:32,540
to various telemetry systems.

287
00:16:33,455 --> 00:16:36,035
The models responsibilities
include understanding natural

288
00:16:36,035 --> 00:16:38,015
language descriptions of incidents.

289
00:16:38,645 --> 00:16:42,845
Generating and refining queries,
synthesizing data into explanations,

290
00:16:42,935 --> 00:16:44,315
timelines and hypothesis.

291
00:16:44,945 --> 00:16:48,275
Typically, this is exposed to engineers
through a chat-based interface.

292
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:52,430
Integrated into tools like
Stack Slack teams or an

293
00:16:52,430 --> 00:16:53,750
incident management dashboards.

294
00:16:54,250 --> 00:16:55,780
Second is the context engineering.

295
00:16:56,380 --> 00:16:59,830
Around the model, we have schema
documentations, curated query libraries,

296
00:17:00,220 --> 00:17:03,130
architecture diagrams, and sometimes
predefined incident playbooks.

297
00:17:03,610 --> 00:17:08,320
This context turns generic LLM into
a domain specific SRE assistant that

298
00:17:08,320 --> 00:17:11,080
understands your system structure
and your telemetry semantics.

299
00:17:11,080 --> 00:17:13,090
Third is the human oversight.

300
00:17:13,600 --> 00:17:16,750
Finally, we preserve a strong
human in the loop model.

301
00:17:17,155 --> 00:17:21,475
The AI can suggest que repose hypothesis,
highlight suspicious patterns, and

302
00:17:21,475 --> 00:17:23,335
even suggest possible remediations.

303
00:17:23,995 --> 00:17:29,515
But critical actions remain under human
control, rolling back deployments,

304
00:17:29,545 --> 00:17:34,075
shifting traffic, declaring major
incidents, communicating externally.

305
00:17:35,065 --> 00:17:39,265
This combination gives us the speed
and breadth of AI driven analysis

306
00:17:39,295 --> 00:17:42,745
while maintaining the safety and
judgment of experienced engineers.

307
00:17:43,245 --> 00:17:45,885
From actually trying to design
and operate systems like this,

308
00:17:45,885 --> 00:17:48,045
a few key lessons emerge.

309
00:17:48,255 --> 00:17:49,695
First lesson is curated query.

310
00:17:49,695 --> 00:17:51,195
Libraries are extremely valuable.

311
00:17:51,945 --> 00:17:54,135
They help standardize how
investigations are done.

312
00:17:54,495 --> 00:17:57,825
They reduce the likelihood of slow,
inefficient, or incorrect queries.

313
00:17:58,395 --> 00:18:01,835
They provide the AI with strong
foundation of known good patents.

314
00:18:02,335 --> 00:18:04,010
Second is the comprehensive schema.

315
00:18:04,210 --> 00:18:05,370
Documentation is essential.

316
00:18:05,870 --> 00:18:08,890
The pre, the more precisely you
document field meanings, units.

317
00:18:09,390 --> 00:18:11,640
Relationships between tables and metrics.

318
00:18:12,120 --> 00:18:16,290
Service naming conventions, the
better your AI assistant will be at

319
00:18:16,290 --> 00:18:18,060
generating precise and useful queries.

320
00:18:18,840 --> 00:18:21,060
Third is the balance
automation with human judgment.

321
00:18:21,480 --> 00:18:25,800
It is tempting to automate everything, but
incidents are often messy and ambiguous.

322
00:18:26,190 --> 00:18:29,160
A practical approach is
you use AI to recommend and

323
00:18:29,160 --> 00:18:31,140
explain, not to silently act.

324
00:18:31,670 --> 00:18:35,330
Start with the readly low risk
automations, such as pre-running a

325
00:18:35,330 --> 00:18:38,060
standard set of DI diagnostic queries.

326
00:18:38,090 --> 00:18:41,780
When an alert fires gradually increase
automation, where you have strong

327
00:18:41,780 --> 00:18:44,000
confidence and clear rollback strategies.

328
00:18:44,660 --> 00:18:48,680
This balanced approach builds the
trust with engineers, prevents over

329
00:18:48,680 --> 00:18:53,150
lines on the AI and lets you scale
up auto automation slowly as you gain

330
00:18:53,150 --> 00:18:54,800
more experience and more confidence.

331
00:18:55,300 --> 00:18:58,630
Looking forward, there are several
promising directions for improving

332
00:18:58,630 --> 00:19:00,160
AI assisted incident response.

333
00:19:00,580 --> 00:19:03,070
First is expanding
incident pattern catalogs.

334
00:19:03,460 --> 00:19:07,000
Over time, organizations see similar
types of incidents again and again

335
00:19:07,450 --> 00:19:08,890
by capturing these as patterns.

336
00:19:08,890 --> 00:19:12,880
For example, typical memory leak
behavior, typical dependency timeout

337
00:19:13,360 --> 00:19:17,325
pattern, misconfigured feature flag,
the AI can recognize similar structure

338
00:19:17,325 --> 00:19:21,645
signatures in the telemetry and suggest
likely root causes more quickly.

339
00:19:22,140 --> 00:19:24,960
Second is the enhanced
model context techniques.

340
00:19:25,650 --> 00:19:29,520
We can improve how we feed context to
the model using automatic retrieval

341
00:19:29,520 --> 00:19:32,880
of free owned documentation,
embedding based search over the past

342
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:36,900
incidents, structured representation
of service, topology and dependencies.

343
00:19:37,400 --> 00:19:40,910
Third is the broader integration with
the tools beyond logs and metrics.

344
00:19:40,970 --> 00:19:43,430
AI agents can connect to CI CD pipeline.

345
00:19:43,775 --> 00:19:47,195
Feature flag systems, ticketing
tools, knowledge bases, and wikis.

346
00:19:47,825 --> 00:19:51,845
This enables end-to-end analysis from
a code change to a deployment, to its

347
00:19:51,845 --> 00:19:56,285
effect on production behavior, and finally
to incident tickets and postmortems.

348
00:19:56,785 --> 00:19:58,885
Fourth is the adaptive
learning from incidents.

349
00:19:59,155 --> 00:20:03,175
After each incident, the system can learn
which queries are were most helpful.

350
00:20:03,565 --> 00:20:06,595
Which hypothesis were correct,
which remediation steps worked.

351
00:20:07,315 --> 00:20:11,125
This allows the AI assistant to get
better with each incident, turning

352
00:20:11,245 --> 00:20:14,545
painful events into long-term
learning and automation opportunities.

353
00:20:15,385 --> 00:20:17,965
All of these directions move us
towards incident response that

354
00:20:17,965 --> 00:20:22,405
is faster, more consistent, and
less dependent on few experts.

355
00:20:22,905 --> 00:20:25,885
If you are considering trying this
approach in your own environment,

356
00:20:26,005 --> 00:20:27,895
here is the simple three step path.

357
00:20:28,810 --> 00:20:31,180
First is assess telemetry maturity.

358
00:20:32,080 --> 00:20:36,130
Ask questions like, are our logs metrics
and traces reasonably consistent?

359
00:20:36,400 --> 00:20:39,340
Do we have clear schemas for
our main telemetry stores?

360
00:20:39,840 --> 00:20:43,070
Can we have reliably, co,
reliably correlate database,

361
00:20:43,070 --> 00:20:44,690
service, region and version?

362
00:20:45,650 --> 00:20:50,410
If the answer to is mostly no, then
your best first investment is not ai.

363
00:20:50,410 --> 00:20:52,570
It is improving the
basic telemetry engine.

364
00:20:53,320 --> 00:20:55,750
Second is the develop context materials.

365
00:20:56,170 --> 00:21:00,320
Once the basics are in place, you can
work on creating schema documentations,

366
00:21:00,800 --> 00:21:05,260
architecture diagrams, curated query
libraries, and short focused run books.

367
00:21:05,710 --> 00:21:08,500
Think of this as a, creating a
knowledge base that both humans

368
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:10,060
and AI can use during incidents.

369
00:21:10,560 --> 00:21:12,719
Step three is the pilot AI diagnostics.

370
00:21:12,799 --> 00:21:17,579
Start with the small choose one or
two services or one specific domain.

371
00:21:17,984 --> 00:21:21,134
Integrate an MCP enabled AI
assistant with read only access.

372
00:21:21,524 --> 00:21:24,644
Use it during real incidents,
always with human oversight.

373
00:21:25,304 --> 00:21:26,414
Then collect feedback.

374
00:21:26,564 --> 00:21:27,794
What did the AI do well?

375
00:21:28,274 --> 00:21:29,894
Where did it struggle or hallucinate?

376
00:21:30,254 --> 00:21:31,964
What additional context would've helped?

377
00:21:32,714 --> 00:21:36,104
I trade on the context, the
guardrails, and the user experience.

378
00:21:36,494 --> 00:21:40,154
Then expand to more services and
more teams as confidence grows.

379
00:21:40,654 --> 00:21:41,859
Thank you everyone for your attention.

